top.value: The Sustainable Trade Platform (STP) is an initiative that promotes partnerships between private companies, the Colombian government and civil society organisations to ensure that the supply of agricultural products in Colombia meets the growing and global demand of sustainable ingredients.  It also aims to position Colombian as a well-established origin for sustainable products.

As part of the Digital Innovation strategy we aim to develop a Network-wide IT platform and approach to support Solidaridad and its partners in analyzing producer performance in the relevant areas of entrepreneurial farming and good practices. These are benchmarked against various standards, including legal standards, market-based quality standards and sustainability (certification) standards. By applying Big Data comparison technology to this analysis, we can bring large numbers of farmers to the next level of sustainable production. As of mid 2017, senior IT capacity came in board throughout the Network and we started a much larger streamlining process of already existing IT solutions in the Network, towards a broader strategic platform offering a series of tools through a suite of apps.

As part of the Digital Solidaridad Sustainability Solutions (3S) strategy, this taskforce aims to develop an ICT platform and approach to support Solidaridad and its partners in analyzing producer performance in the relevant areas of entrepreneurial farming and good practices. These are benchmarked against various standards, including legal standards, market-based quality standards and sustainability (certification) standards. By applying Big Data comparison technology to this analysis, we can bring large numbers of farmers to the next level of sustainable production. We are currently using the data gathering and information delivering platform in collaboration with major companies and leading producer associations.

Although we are an active participant in the Roundtable for Responsible Soy (RTRS), the standard has remained too niche, unable to address important issues as deforestation and Land Use Change; women’s empowerment and leadership; soy as a source of food and nutrition; and productivity and income increases for the case of Africa. Therefore we looked to strengthen other initiatives at a more national and local level, including the Sustainable Soy Trade Platform (SSTP) in China, the National Soy Trade Platform in India, and supporting a recent discussion to set a national guidance in Argentina. In Paraguay, Solidaridad is participating in the National Committee of Ecology and Environment organized by the National Chamber of Deputies, as well as, the National Committee of Climate Change, held by the Ministry of Environment and Sustainable Development and the National Institution of Forestry. In Brazil, Solidaridad is joining the discussion of the Cerrado Working Group (GTC). In addition, in Europe, we are participating in the dialogue for the European Soy Coalition and the Amsterdam Declaration.
